WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.550 --> 00:00:03.150
&gt;&gt; Sasha Dowdy: Good
afternoon, everyone.

00:00:03.150 --> 00:00:05.460
I hope you all had a good lunch.

00:00:05.460 --> 00:00:07.150
Doing great.

00:00:07.150 --> 00:00:10.720
So welcome to the Library of
Congress National Book Festival.

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:12.990
My name is Sasha Dowdy,
I work at the Library

00:00:12.990 --> 00:00:14.870
of Congress Young
Readers' Center,

00:00:14.870 --> 00:00:18.550
which is a really special place
in the Library of Congress

00:00:18.550 --> 00:00:20.480
for kids, teens,
and their families.

00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:22.670
For everybody who's
under 16 years old.

00:00:22.670 --> 00:00:25.860
And you can come take a
look into the millions

00:00:25.860 --> 00:00:27.690
of collections at the library.

00:00:27.690 --> 00:00:32.400
The Library of Congress National
Book Festival recognizes

00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:35.540
and celebrates the importance of
reading and authors and books.

00:00:35.540 --> 00:00:38.860
The Library of Congress makes it
seem easy to do this every year,

00:00:38.860 --> 00:00:42.960
but the truth is the library
festival is a huge undertaking.

00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:45.490
It's a huge financial
undertaking and it is free

00:00:45.490 --> 00:00:47.740
for everyone because
of the generous support

00:00:47.740 --> 00:00:49.860
from our sponsors
and supporters.

00:00:49.860 --> 00:00:52.120
Spread the joy of reading
with your gift online

00:00:52.120 --> 00:00:56.240
on LOC.gov/donate,
from the Festival app,

00:00:56.240 --> 00:00:58.090
or when you purchase
books today.

00:00:58.090 --> 00:01:00.360
And now onto the main event.

00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:03.510
We have here author
Russell Ginns!

00:01:03.510 --> 00:01:08.050
[ Applause ]

00:01:08.050 --> 00:01:09.360
When I was reading a
little bit about him,

00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:13.400
I realized that he is a very
unique author whose books

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:15.880
and works can be found
everywhere in the library.

00:01:15.880 --> 00:01:17.760
So he's a game designer.

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:20.230
So they can be found in the
movie and game division.

00:01:20.230 --> 00:01:23.980
And he's also a composer,
so you can find music

00:01:23.980 --> 00:01:27.540
in our performing arts library.

00:01:27.540 --> 00:01:28.910
And he is a puzzle maker.

00:01:28.910 --> 00:01:31.040
And those things you
can find anywhere

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:35.410
within our 167 million
item collection.

00:01:35.410 --> 00:01:37.850
And I challenge you
guys to come find them.

00:01:37.850 --> 00:01:39.820
And of course, Russell
writes books.

00:01:39.820 --> 00:01:42.280
He's written over 100 books.

00:01:42.280 --> 00:01:45.280
They are fun, they're smart,
and they're full of adventure.

00:01:45.280 --> 00:01:48.350
So buckle in, and you're
going to find out more about

00:01:48.350 --> 00:01:50.780
"Samantha Spinner and
the Super Secret Plans."

00:01:50.780 --> 00:01:53.420
It's a spectacular journey
through Seattle, Washington,

00:01:53.420 --> 00:01:56.510
Paris, and other countries and
cities that I won't tell you

00:01:56.510 --> 00:01:59.830
about because they're
super secret.

00:01:59.830 --> 00:02:02.510
So, welcome Russell
Ginns, everybody!

00:02:02.510 --> 00:02:07.060
[ Applause ]

00:02:07.060 --> 00:02:08.840
&gt;&gt; Russell Ginns: Testing, okay!

00:02:08.840 --> 00:02:11.170
Well, thank you guys.

00:02:11.170 --> 00:02:14.890
It is a huge thrill to
be at the book festival.

00:02:14.890 --> 00:02:17.370
So I want to start
by saying thank you.

00:02:17.370 --> 00:02:20.290
I'm probably going to say
thank you a couple times.

00:02:20.290 --> 00:02:23.410
And I am here to talk to
you about my new book series

00:02:23.410 --> 00:02:27.050
"Samantha Spinner and
the Super Secret Plans."

00:02:27.050 --> 00:02:29.420
Where Samantha's
uncle disappeared.

00:02:29.420 --> 00:02:32.090
But before he took
off, he taught Samantha

00:02:32.090 --> 00:02:35.090
and her brother how to
say please, thank you,

00:02:35.090 --> 00:02:36.440
and "where's the
tallest building?"

00:02:36.440 --> 00:02:38.200
in 11 different languages.

00:02:38.200 --> 00:02:41.350
And they set off to find
them and they discover

00:02:41.350 --> 00:02:44.950
that no place is in
the middle of nowhere.

